ROOT CAUSE: The loop counter `i` is declared as a `size_t` (an unsigned integer type), making the loop condition `i >= 0` always evaluate to true. When the loop finishes processing the element at index 0 and decrements `i` (which becomes `size_t`'s maximum value), the loop condition remains true and proceeds to access `v[i]` at an out-of-bounds index, causing a memory access error.

LOCAL FIX: A common fix is to change the loop condition to account for the unsigned nature of the counter, for example by checking `i != static_cast<size_t>(-1)` or by using a signed integer for the index while keeping it within the valid bounds of the vector. A safer approach is to use a `while` loop or change the condition:
```cpp
for (size_t i = v.size(); i-- > 0; ) {
    std::printf("%d\n", v[i]);
}
```

GLOBAL FIX: To prevent this entire class of bugs, prefer using C++ Standard Library features such as `std::reverse_iterator` or `std::ranges::views::reverse` (if available, e.g., C++20). These abstractions clearly express the intent of iterating in reverse without requiring manual management of loop counter indices, thus guaranteeing safety and improving code readability.

